==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*sunu-'', from Indo-European ''*seu-, *sū-'' ‘give birth, reproduce’.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian ''sunu'', Old Saxon ''sunu'' (Dutch [[zoon]]), Old High German ''sunu'' (German [[Sohn]]), Old Norse [[sunr]], [[sonr]] (Swedish [[son]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌿𐌽𐌿𐍃]].  The IE root is also the source of Sanskrit [[सूनुह्]] ‘son’, Lithuanian [[sunus|sūnùs]], Old Church Slavonic [[сынъ]] (Russian [[сын]]); and more distantly of Greek [[υἱύς]], Old Irish [[suth]] ‘birth, fruit’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'sʊnʊ/

===Noun===
'''sunu''' ''m'' (''gen'' '''suna''')
# a [[son]], a male child

